## Important Notes

- The mapper uses `as Record<string, unknown>` casts because the SDK's `SDKMessage` type is a union that doesn't expose all fields at the type level. This follows the exact same pattern as the existing `system/init` handler on line 22 and the `result` handler on line 118.
- The `output_file` field from `task_notification` is intentionally NOT mapped — it's a filesystem path that should not be exposed to the client (security consideration from the spec).
- The scenario builders return `SDKMessage` (not typed subtypes) because the mapper accepts `SDKMessage`. This matches the existing pattern used by `makeInit`, `makeResult`, etc.

## Acceptance Criteria

1. `pnpm vitest run apps/server/src/services/runtimes/claude-code/__tests__/sdk-event-mapper.test.ts` passes all 6 test cases
2. `pnpm vitest run apps/server/src/services/runtimes/claude-code/__tests__/sdk-scenarios.test.ts` passes (existing tests + 3 new builder tests)
3. `pnpm typecheck` passes — the mapper yields valid `StreamEvent` objects with the new event types
4. The existing `system/init` handling is unaffected (init messages still set `session.sdkSessionId`)
5. Unknown system subtypes (e.g., 'status', 'compact_boundary') still produce no events

Add three new switch cases to the client's stream event handler and a `findSubagentPart` helper function. Update `deriveFromParts` to skip SubagentParts.

## File to Modify

`apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/model/stream-event-handler.ts`

### 1. Add Type Imports

Update the import block at the top of the file (line 1-10) to include the three new event types:

```typescript
import type {
  TextDelta,
  ToolCallEvent,
  ApprovalEvent,
  QuestionPromptEvent,
  ErrorEvent,
  SessionStatusEvent,
  TaskUpdateEvent,
  MessagePart,
  SubagentStartedEvent,
  SubagentProgressEvent,
  SubagentDoneEvent,
} from '@dorkos/shared/types';
```

### 2. Add `findSubagentPart` Helper

Add this function inside `createStreamEventHandler`, right after the existing `findToolCallPart` function (after line 94):

```typescript
  function findSubagentPart(taskId: string) {
    for (let i = currentPartsRef.current.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
      const part = currentPartsRef.current[i];
      if (part.type === 'subagent' && part.taskId === taskId) {
        return part;
      }
    }
    return undefined;
  }
```

This follows the exact same reverse-iteration pattern as `findToolCallPart` (lines 86-94) — searching from the end is more efficient since the most recent part is most likely the target.

### 3. Add Three Switch Cases

Add three new cases in the `handleStreamEvent` switch statement, after the `task_update` case (after line 285) and before the `done` case (line 287):

```typescript
      case 'subagent_started': {
        const { taskId, description } = data as SubagentStartedEvent;
        currentPartsRef.current.push({
          type: 'subagent',
          taskId,
          description,
          status: 'running',
        });
        updateAssistantMessage(assistantId);
        break;
      }

      case 'subagent_progress': {
        const progress = data as SubagentProgressEvent;
        const subagentPart = findSubagentPart(progress.taskId);
        if (subagentPart) {
          subagentPart.toolUses = progress.toolUses;
          subagentPart.lastToolName = progress.lastToolName;
          subagentPart.durationMs = progress.durationMs;
        }
        updateAssistantMessage(assistantId);
        break;
      }

      case 'subagent_done': {
        const done = data as SubagentDoneEvent;
        const subagentPartDone = findSubagentPart(done.taskId);
        if (subagentPartDone) {
          subagentPartDone.status = done.status === 'completed' ? 'complete' : 'error';
          subagentPartDone.summary = done.summary;
          if (done.toolUses !== undefined) subagentPartDone.toolUses = done.toolUses;
          if (done.durationMs !== undefined) subagentPartDone.durationMs = done.durationMs;
        }
        updateAssistantMessage(assistantId);
        break;
      }
```

### 4. Update `deriveFromParts`

Modify the `deriveFromParts` function (lines 41-61) so that SubagentParts are explicitly skipped. Change the `else` branch to an explicit `else if` for tool_call parts:

```typescript
export function deriveFromParts(parts: MessagePart[]): { content: string; toolCalls: ToolCallState[] } {
  const textSegments: string[] = [];
  const toolCalls: ToolCallState[] = [];
  for (const part of parts) {
    if (part.type === 'text') {
      textSegments.push(part.text);
    } else if (part.type === 'tool_call') {
      toolCalls.push({
        toolCallId: part.toolCallId,
        toolName: part.toolName,
        input: part.input || '',
        result: part.result,
        status: part.status,
        interactiveType: part.interactiveType,
        questions: part.questions,
        answers: part.answers,
      });
    }
    // SubagentParts are intentionally skipped — they render via their own component
  }
  return { content: textSegments.join('\n'), toolCalls };
}
```

The key change: `} else {` becomes `} else if (part.type === 'tool_call') {`. This ensures that when a SubagentPart appears in the parts array, it doesn't get treated as a tool call (which would cause a runtime error accessing `part.toolCallId` on a SubagentPart).

## Important Notes

- The `subagent_started` handler pushes a new part with `type: 'subagent'` — this is the `SubagentPart` type added to the `MessagePartSchema` discriminated union in task 1.1.
- The `subagent_done` handler maps SDK status `'completed'` to part status `'complete'` and both `'failed'` and `'stopped'` to `'error'`. This matches the `SubagentStatusSchema` enum values: `'running' | 'complete' | 'error'`.
- `subagent_progress` mutates the existing part directly (same pattern as `tool_call_delta` on line 182-183), then calls `updateAssistantMessage` which creates a shallow copy.
- No `queueMicrotask` deferral needed for subagent events (unlike `tool_result` on line 217) because subagent events don't produce adjacent orphan text parts.

## Acceptance Criteria

1. `pnpm typecheck` passes — the new event types are correctly imported and used
2. When a `subagent_started` event arrives, a new SubagentPart is pushed to `currentPartsRef.current`
3. When a `subagent_progress` event arrives, the matching SubagentPart's `toolUses`, `lastToolName`, and `durationMs` are updated
4. When a `subagent_done` event arrives, the matching SubagentPart's `status` is set to `'complete'` or `'error'` and `summary` is populated
5. `deriveFromParts` returns empty `toolCalls` array and empty `content` string when given only SubagentParts
6. `deriveFromParts` still works correctly for mixed parts arrays (text + tool_call + subagent)

Create a new `SubagentBlock.tsx` component that renders the subagent lifecycle inline block with status icons, progress metrics, and an expand/collapse animation.

## File to Create

`apps/client/src/layers/features/chat/ui/SubagentBlock.tsx`

This component follows the same patterns as `ToolCallCard.tsx` in the same directory. It uses the `toolStatus` CVA from `message-variants.ts` for status icon coloring.

### Full Component Implementation

```tsx
import { useState } from 'react';
import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'motion/react';
import { Loader2, Check, X, ChevronDown } from 'lucide-react';
import type { SubagentPart } from '@dorkos/shared/types';
import { cn } from '@/layers/shared/lib';
import { toolStatus } from './message/message-variants';

interface SubagentBlockProps {
  part: SubagentPart;
}

/** Format duration from milliseconds to human-readable string. */
function formatDuration(ms: number): string {
  if (ms < 1000) return '<1s';
  const seconds = Math.floor(ms / 1000);
  if (seconds < 60) return `${seconds}s`;
  const minutes = Math.floor(seconds / 60);
  const remainingSeconds = seconds % 60;
  return `${minutes}m ${remainingSeconds}s`;
}

/** Build a tool usage summary string from subagent progress metrics. */
function buildToolSummary(part: SubagentPart): string | null {
  const segments: string[] = [];
  if (part.toolUses) {
    segments.push(`${part.toolUses} tool ${part.toolUses === 1 ? 'call' : 'calls'}`);
  }
  if (part.durationMs) {
    segments.push(formatDuration(part.durationMs));
  }
  return segments.length > 0 ? segments.join(' \u00b7 ') : null;
}

/** Collapsible inline block displaying a subagent's lifecycle status. */
export function SubagentBlock({ part }: SubagentBlockProps) {
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(false);

  const statusIcon = {
    running: <Loader2 className={cn('size-(--size-icon-xs) animate-spin', toolStatus({ status: 'running' }))} />,
    complete: <Check className={cn('size-(--size-icon-xs)', toolStatus({ status: 'complete' }))} />,
    error: <X className={cn('size-(--size-icon-xs)', toolStatus({ status: 'error' }))} />,
  }[part.status];

  const toolSummary = buildToolSummary(part);
  const hasExpandableContent = toolSummary || part.summary || part.lastToolName;

  return (
    <div
      className="bg-muted/50 hover:border-border mt-px rounded-msg-tool border text-sm shadow-msg-tool transition-all duration-150 first:mt-1 hover:shadow-msg-tool-hover"
      data-testid="subagent-block"
      data-task-id={part.taskId}
      data-status={part.status}
    >
      <button
        onClick={() => hasExpandableContent && setExpanded(!expanded)}
        className="flex w-full items-center gap-2 px-3 py-1"
        aria-expanded={hasExpandableContent ? expanded : undefined}
        aria-label={`Subagent: ${part.description}`}
      >
        {statusIcon}
        <span className="text-3xs font-mono truncate">{part.description}</span>
        {toolSummary && (
          <span className="text-3xs text-muted-foreground ml-1 shrink-0">{toolSummary}</span>
        )}
        {hasExpandableContent && (
          <motion.div
            animate={{ rotate: expanded ? 180 : 0 }}
            transition={{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 400, damping: 30 }}
            className="ml-auto"
          >
            <ChevronDown className="size-(--size-icon-xs)" />
          </motion.div>
        )}
      </button>
      <AnimatePresence initial={false}>
        {expanded && hasExpandableContent && (
          <motion.div
            initial={{ height: 0, opacity: 0 }}
            animate={{ height: 'auto', opacity: 1 }}
            exit={{ height: 0, opacity: 0 }}
            transition={{ duration: 0.3, ease: [0.4, 0, 0.2, 1] }}
            className="overflow-hidden"
          >
            <div className="border-t px-3 pt-1 pb-3 space-y-1">
              {part.lastToolName && part.status === 'running' && (
                <p className="text-3xs text-muted-foreground">
                  Last tool: <span className="font-mono">{part.lastToolName}</span>
                </p>
              )}
              {part.summary && (
                <pre className="text-xs whitespace-pre-wrap overflow-x-auto">
                  {part.summary}
                </pre>
              )}
            </div>
          </motion.div>
        )}
      </AnimatePresence>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Design Decisions

### Visual Consistency with ToolCallCard

The component intentionally mirrors `ToolCallCard.tsx` patterns:
- Same `bg-muted/50`, `rounded-msg-tool`, `shadow-msg-tool` container classes
- Same `text-3xs font-mono` for the label text
- Same `motion/react` AnimatePresence expand/collapse pattern
- Same chevron rotation spring animation (`stiffness: 400, damping: 30`)
- Same `toolStatus` CVA variants for status icon coloring from `message-variants.ts`

### Status Icon Mapping

| SubagentPart status | Icon | CVA variant | Visual |
|---|---|---|---|
| `running` | `Loader2` (spinning) | `toolStatus({ status: 'running' })` | Blue spinner |
| `complete` | `Check` | `toolStatus({ status: 'complete' })` | Green checkmark |
| `error` | `X` | `toolStatus({ status: 'error' })` | Red X |

### Expandable Content Rules

- The expanded section shows "Last tool" only during `running` state (it's stale once complete)
- The expanded section shows the `summary` text when available (populated by `subagent_done`)
- If there is no expandable content (no `toolSummary`, no `summary`, no `lastToolName`), the chevron is hidden and clicking is a no-op
- `aria-expanded` is only set when expandable content exists (per WAI-ARIA best practices)

### `formatDuration` Function

- `< 1000ms` → `'<1s'`
- `1000-59999ms` → `'Ns'` (e.g., `'5s'`, `'42s'`)
- `60000ms+` → `'Nm Ns'` (e.g., `'1m 30s'`, `'3m 0s'`)

### `buildToolSummary` Function

- Produces strings like `'3 tool calls · 5s'`, `'1 tool call'`, `'12s'`
- Returns `null` if no metrics are present (early subagent_started with no progress yet)
- Uses Unicode middle dot (U+00B7) as separator

## Data Attributes for Testing

- `data-testid="subagent-block"` — find the block in tests
- `data-task-id` — correlate with task ID
- `data-status` — assert status transitions

## Acceptance Criteria

1. Component renders without errors for all three statuses: `running`, `complete`, `error`
2. Spinner animation plays on `running` status via `animate-spin` class on `Loader2`
3. Tool summary text updates reactively when `part.toolUses` or `part.durationMs` change
4. Expand/collapse animation works via `AnimatePresence`
5. No chevron rendered when there is no expandable content
6. `aria-label` includes the subagent description for screen readers
7. `data-testid="subagent-block"` is present for test queries

